            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Cuisine in the land of cherry blossoms</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Food in Japan is divided into two main areas: tempura and sushi. Tempura is a type of cooked food, while sushi is fresh, even raw food. Japanese dishes aim to be fresh, pure and nutritious for health.</p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/Home/Handbook/Japan/japan-4.jpg" width="100%" />
            <p class="note-img">Tempura</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">If possible, go to luxury stores to enjoy the dishes here, but if not, you can go to more popular stores to enjoy them. In addition, you can also find dishes from other countries such as Taiwan, India, Vietnam,... from street shops. In general, Japanese dishes are quite easy to eat, but just in case you don't like it here, you should bring boxed instant noodles for convenience!</p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/Home/Handbook/Japan/japan-5.jpg" width="100%" />
            <p class="note-img">Sushi</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Some famous dishes that those who travel to Japan should try: Sushi, Sukiyaki, Tempura, Ramen, Okonomiyaki, Unagi no kabayaki, Yakitori, Sanuki udon, Tonkatsu, Natto, Gyoza, Nabe, Miso soup, Soba noodles, Taiyaki - grilled fish cake, matcha ice cream,...</p>

